    summary: "Given a non-negative integer n, return an array of length n+1 where each element at index i holds the number of 1-bits in the binary representation of i.",
    approach: "- Use dynamic programming: the popcount of i equals the popcount of i right-shifted by one (i.e., `i/2`) plus the least-significant bit of i (`i & 1`).\n- This works because dropping the last bit gives a smaller number already in the table, and we only need to add back whether that dropped bit was set.\n- A single left-to-right pass fills the table in O(n) time with no calls to any library bit-count function.",
    code: "#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    vector<int> countBits(int n) {\n        vector<int> dp(n + 1, 0);\n        // dp[i] = dp[i >> 1] + (i & 1)\n        // \"shift right\" gives a previously computed value;\n        // add 1 if the original LSB was set.\n        for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {\n            dp[i] = dp[i >> 1] + (i & 1);\n        }\n        return dp;\n    }\n};",
