    summary: "Design a class that stores an integer array and supports two operations: returning the array to its original order, and producing a uniformly random permutation of the array where every arrangement is equally likely.",
    approach: "- Store a copy of the original array at construction time so `reset()` can return it in O(n).\n- Use the Fisher-Yates (Knuth) shuffle for `shuffle()`: iterate index `i` from 0 to n-1, pick a random index `j` in `[i, n-1]`, and swap elements at `i` and `j`.\n- Each of the n! permutations is produced with equal probability because at step `i` there are exactly `n-i` remaining positions to choose from, and the choices are independent.\n- Use a seeded Mersenne Twister (`mt19937`) with `std::uniform_int_distribution` for high-quality, unbiased randomness.",
    code: "#include <vector>\n#include <random>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\n    vector<int> original;          // immutable reference copy\n    mt19937 rng{random_device{}()}; // seeded Mersenne Twister\n\npublic:\n    Solution(vector<int>& nums) : original(nums) {}\n\n    // Return the array to its original configuration.\n    vector<int> reset() {\n        return original;\n    }\n\n    // Return a uniformly random permutation via Fisher-Yates shuffle.\n    vector<int> shuffle() {\n        vector<int> arr = original;\n        int n = arr.size();\n        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {\n            // Pick a random index in [i, n-1] and swap into position i.\n            uniform_int_distribution<int> dist(i, n - 1);\n            swap(arr[i], arr[dist(rng)]);\n        }\n        return arr;\n    }\n};\n\n/**\n * Your Solution object will be instantiated and called as such:\n * Solution* obj = new Solution(nums);\n * vector<int> param_1 = obj->reset();\n * vector<int> param_2 = obj->shuffle();\n */",
