    routeSlug: "45-jump-game-ii",
    summary: "Given an integer array where each element represents the maximum jump length from that position, find the minimum number of jumps needed to reach the last index from the first index.",
    approach: "- Use a greedy \"implicit BFS levels\" approach: treat each jump as a level, tracking the farthest reachable index within the current level.\n- Maintain two pointers: `currentEnd` (the boundary of the current jump's reach) and `farthest` (the maximum index reachable from any position seen so far).\n- When the loop reaches `currentEnd`, a new jump must be taken — increment the counter and advance `currentEnd` to `farthest`.\n- This works because at each boundary we greedily extend as far as possible, guaranteeing the fewest jumps to cover the array.",
    code: "#include <vector>\n#include <algorithm>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    int jump(vector<int>& nums) {\n        int n = nums.size();\n        int jumps = 0;\n        int currentEnd = 0; // boundary of the current jump level\n        int farthest = 0;   // farthest index reachable so far\n\n        // Only iterate up to n-2: once currentEnd reaches or passes n-1 we're done\n        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; ++i) {\n            farthest = max(farthest, i + nums[i]);\n\n            // Reached the end of the current jump level — must take another jump\n            if (i == currentEnd) {\n                ++jumps;\n                currentEnd = farthest;\n                if (currentEnd >= n - 1) break; // already can reach the last index\n            }\n        }\n\n        return jumps;\n    }\n};",
