    approach: "- Build a prefix-sum array once in the constructor so that each index `i` owns the half-open interval `[prefixSum[i-1], prefixSum[i])` on the number line `[0, total)`.\n- On each `pickIndex()` call, draw a random integer `target` in `[0, total)` via `rand() % prefix.back()` and use `upper_bound` to locate the first prefix-sum entry strictly greater than `target` — that entry's index is the answer.\n- This works because `target` falls in `[prefixSum[i-1], prefixSum[i]-1]` for some `i`, and `upper_bound` returns a pointer to `prefixSum[i]` (the first element strictly greater), yielding index `i` directly.",
    code: "#include <vector>\n#include <numeric>\n#include <algorithm>\n#include <cstdlib>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\n    vector<int> prefix; // prefix[i] = sum of w[0..i]\npublic:\n    // O(n) — build cumulative weight array once\n    Solution(vector<int>& w) {\n        prefix.resize(w.size());\n        partial_sum(w.begin(), w.end(), prefix.begin());\n    }\n\n    // O(log n) — binary-search for the interval that contains the random target\n    int pickIndex() {\n        // Draw uniformly from [0, total)\n        int target = rand() % prefix.back();\n        // upper_bound finds first prefix entry > target, which is exactly\n        // the index whose weight-interval contains target.\n        return static_cast<int>(\n            upper_bound(prefix.begin(), prefix.end(), target) - prefix.begin()\n        );\n    }\n};\n\n/**\n * Your Solution object will be instantiated and called as such:\n * Solution* obj = new Solution(w);\n * int param_1 = obj->pickIndex();\n */\n",
    timeComplexity: "O(n) constructor, O(log n) per pickIndex()",
