    approach: "- Extract digits one at a time using `% 10` and build the reversed number by multiplying the running result by 10 each step.\n- Before each multiply-and-add, check whether the new result would exceed `INT_MAX` or fall below `INT_MIN` using the guard `result > INT_MAX / 10` (and the boundary digit check).\n- This overflow detection works entirely in integer arithmetic — no 64-bit types or bit tricks needed — making it portable across every 32-bit signed platform.\n- The loop naturally handles negative numbers because C++ integer division and modulo preserve the sign of the dividend.",
    code: "#include <climits>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    int reverse(int x) {\n        int result = 0;\n\n        while (x != 0) {\n            int digit = x % 10;  // preserves sign for negative x\n            x /= 10;\n\n            // Overflow check before updating result:\n            //   INT_MAX = 2147483647  → last digit bound is 7\n            //   INT_MIN = -2147483648 → last digit bound is -8\n            if (result > INT_MAX / 10 || (result == INT_MAX / 10 && digit > 7))\n                return 0;\n            if (result < INT_MIN / 10 || (result == INT_MIN / 10 && digit < -8))\n                return 0;\n\n            result = result * 10 + digit;\n        }\n\n        return result;\n    }\n};\n",
